== Limitations at Higher Precision

The linear spline approach works well for lns8 and lns16,
because the domain of the correction functions is small $-$
the argument $x = L_y - L_x$ ranges over at most 8 or 16 bits, respectively.
For lns32 and lns64, the domain grows proportionally with the exponent width,
and the number of intervals required to maintain a fixed error bound scales roughly
as $O(sqrt(1/epsilon)) = O(sqrt(1/(2^(-n)))) = O(2^(n/2))$ per unit of domain,
making table-based approaches impractical.

Additionally, even for lns8 and lns16 there is room to improve approximation quality beyond piecewise linear.
Higher-degree polynomial approximations can achieve the same error with fewer segments or lower error with the
same number of segments.

= Candidate Approximation Methods

This chapter surveys the methods under consideration for replacing or supplementing linear splines for lns8,
lns16, and for use in lns32 and lns64.

== Error Formula

#block(
  stroke: 0.5pt,
  inset: 10pt,
  radius: 4pt,
)[
  *Theorem 1* Lagrange Interpolation Error Formula

  Given a function $f(x) in C^(n+1)[a,b]$, let $p_n (x) in bb(P)_n$ be the interpolative 
  polynomial of $f(x)$ in the unique $x$'s ${x_i | 0 <= i <= n}$, then $forall x in [a,b],
  exists c_x in [a,b]:$

  $
    epsilon = f(x) - p_n (x) = 1 / (n+1)! f^((n+1))(c_x) pi_(n+1)(x)
  $

  where $pi_(n+1)(x) = product_(k=0)^n (x - x_k)$
]


=== $f^+$ and $f^-$ Error Upper Bound

Given $x < 0$:

#math.equation(numbering: none, block: true)[
$
log_2(1 plus.minus 2^x) &= 1/ln(2) ln(1 plus.minus 2^x) \
&= 1/ln(2) integral_(-infinity)^x dif/(dif t) \(ln(1 plus.minus 2^t)\) dif t \
&= 1/ln(2) integral_(-infinity)^x 1/(1 plus.minus 2^t) dif/(dif t)(1 plus.minus 2^t) dif t \
&= plus.minus/ln(2) integral_(-infinity)^x (2^t)/(1 plus.minus 2^t) dif t \
$
]

As $plus.minus 2^t < 0, forall t in (-infinity, x], x < 0$, then $1/(1 plus.minus 2^t)$ can be expanded using the geometric series \
infinite series representation $1 / (1 - r) = sum_(i>=0) r^n$.

#math.equation(numbering: none, block: true)[
$
&= plus.minus/ln(2) integral_(-infinity)^x 2^t sum_(n>=0) (minus.plus 2^(t))^n dif t \
$
]

Since the series converges, the swap of the integration and sumation operations are justified.

#math.equation(numbering: none, block: true)[
$
&= plus.minus/ln(2) sum_(n>=0) (minus.plus 1)^n integral_(-infinity)^x 2^((n + 1) t) dif t \
&= 1/ln(2) sum_(n>=0) (minus.plus 1)^(n-1) lr((1/(ln(2)(n+1)) 2^((n+1) t)) bar.v)_(t->-infinity)^(t=x) \
&= 1/ln(2)^2 sum_(n>=0) (minus.plus 1)^(n-1)/(n+1) 2^((n+1) x) \
&= 1/ln(2)^2 sum_(n>=1) (minus.plus 1)^n/n 2^(n x) \
$
]

And so, we finally get an infinite series representation of $f^+$ and $f^-$.

$
log_2(1 plus.minus 2^x) = 1/ln(2)^2 sum_(n>=1) (minus.plus 1)^n/n 2^(n x), x < 0
$

Now, we can use this infinite series representation to calculate an upper bound for the k-th derivative of both functions:

#math.equation(numbering: none, block: true)[
$
dif^k/(dif x^k) log_2(1 plus.minus 2^x) &= 1/ln(2)^2 dif^k/(dif x^k) sum_(n>=1) (minus.plus 1)^n/n 2^(n x) \
$
]

The switch of the summation and derivative operators is also justified as the series does converge.

#math.equation(numbering: none, block: true)[
$
dif^k/(dif x^k) log_2(1 plus.minus 2^x) &= 1/ln(2)^2 sum_(n>=1) (minus.plus 1)^n/n dif^k/(dif x^k) 2^(n x) \
dif^k/(dif x^k) log_2(1 plus.minus 2^x) &= ln(2)^(k-2) sum_(n>=1) (minus.plus 1)^n n^(k-1) 2^(n x) \
$
]

If we can find a term $a$, such that all terms $n^(k-1) 2^(n x) <= a^n$, then the sum of the terms will be larger than our current series and we have a simple upper bound we can compute.

Following the Alternative Series Estimation Error for $f^+$, \
as $|a_(n+1)| < |a_n| and lim_(n->infinity) a_n = 0, a_n = (minus 1)^n n^(k-1) 2^(n x)$:

#math.equation(numbering: none, block: true)[
$
|a_(n+1)| &< |a_n| \
|(n+1)^(k-1) 2^((n+1)x)| &< |n^(k-1) 2^(n x)| \
(1 + 1/n)^(k-1) &< 2^(-x) \
1 + 1/n &< 2^(-x/(k-1)) \
1/n &< 2^(-x/(k-1)) - 1 \
n &> 1/(2^(-x/(k-1)) - 1) \
$
]

#math.equation(numbering: none, block: true)[
$
|R_n| &< |a_(n+1)| \
\
lr(|sum_(n>=ceil(1/(2^(-x/(k-1)) - 1))) (minus 1)^n n^(k-1) 2^(n x)|) &< lr(|(ceil(1/(2^(-x/(k-1)) - 1))+1)^(k-1) 2^((1+1) x)|) \
&= (ceil(1/(2^(-x/(k-1)) - 1)) + 1)^(k-1) 2^(2x) \
&= (ceil(2^(x/(k-1))/(1 - 2^(x/(k-1)))) + 1)^(k-1) 2^(2x) \
$

$
ceil(2^t/(1-2^t)) + 1
&<= 2^t/(1-2^t) + 2 \
&= (2^t + 2 - 2 dot 2^t)/(1-2^t) \
&= (2 - 2^t)/(1-2^t) \
&= 2(1 - 2^(t-1))/(1-2^t) \
$

$
x < 0 &-> x/(k-1) < 0 -> t < 0\
2(1 - 2^(t-1))/(1-2^t) &<= 1/(1-2^t)\
$

$
(1/(1 - 2^(x/(k-1))))^(k - 1) &= sum_(n >= 0) 2^(x/(k-1))
$

\

$
K &= lr(|sum_(n>=1)^(n = ceil(1/(1 - 2^(x/(k-1))) - 1) - 1) (-1)^n n^(k-1) 2^(n x)|)
$
]

